            <a name="rules"></a>
            <table class="wb-cellspace-1 wb-cellpad-3 wb-rules-section wb-table" style="width: 100%;">
                <tr><td class="BoardColumn"><strong>Board Rules</strong></td></tr>
                <tr><td class="BoardRowB">
                    <p><strong>Use common sense and do not make the moderators babysit you.</strong></p>
                    <ol>
                        <li><strong>Stay on topic.</strong> Use the right board when possible. A little drift is normal; deliberate derailing is not.</li>
                        <li><strong>No harassment or personal attacks.</strong> Criticize ideas, posts, games, companies, and decisions. Do not target people with abuse, threats, stalking, or dogpiling.</li>
                        <li><strong>No hate or dehumanizing content.</strong> Slurs, calls for violence, and attacks based on protected traits are not welcome here.</li>
                        <li><strong>No spam or low-effort flooding.</strong> Do not post empty replies, repeated messages, referral links, scams, or junk just to raise your post count or star rank.</li>
                        <li><strong>No illegal content or instructions.</strong> Do not post pirated software, stolen material, malware, credential dumps, or instructions for abuse.</li>
                        <li><strong>Respect privacy.</strong> Do not post someone else's private information, private messages, real name, address, phone number, or off-site account details without permission.</li>
                        <li><strong>Keep adult or graphic content off the public boards.</strong> Do not post pornography, shock images, gore, or extreme content.</li>
                        <li><strong>Use spoiler warnings when appropriate.</strong> Give people a fair chance to avoid major spoilers for games, shows, books, and events.</li>
                        <li><strong>Do not evade moderation.</strong> If you are banned, suspended, or asked to stop doing something, do not create alternate accounts to continue it.</li>
                        <li><strong>Moderator decisions are not public combat.</strong> If you think a decision was wrong, contact staff calmly. Public flamewars about moderation may be removed.</li>
                    </ol>
                    <p><span class="SmallText">Moderators may edit, move, lock, delete, restore, or archive content as needed. Severe or repeated problems may result in loss of posting privileges.</span></p>
                </td></tr>
            </table>

            <a name="conduct"></a>
            <table class="wb-cellspace-1 wb-cellpad-3 wb-rules-section wb-table" style="width: 100%;">
                <tr><td class="BoardColumn"><strong>Code of Conduct</strong></td></tr>
                <tr><td class="BoardRowB">
                    <p><strong>Assume there are real people behind the usernames.</strong> A good forum can handle disagreement, sarcasm, old rivalries, and blunt opinions. It cannot work if every thread turns into personal abuse.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Be direct without being cruel.</strong> You can tell someone they are wrong without trying to humiliate them.</li>
                        <li><strong>Argue in good faith.</strong> Do not intentionally misquote, bait, sealion, brigade, or derail.</li>
                        <li><strong>Give newcomers a chance.</strong> Point them to the right place instead of turning every mistake into a pile-on.</li>
                        <li><strong>Preserve the archive.</strong> Old posts are part of the site's history. Do not vandalize threads, spam archive boards, or intentionally damage context.</li>
                        <li><strong>Report problems instead of escalating them.</strong> Use the report link when a post or private message needs staff attention.</li>
                        <li><strong>Accept staff calls and move on.</strong> You can appeal politely, but continuing the same behavior after a warning will make things worse.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>The goal is not to make the board sterile. The goal is to keep it usable, readable, and worth preserving.</p>
                </td></tr>
            </table>

            <a name="faq"></a>
            <table class="wb-cellspace-1 wb-cellpad-3 wb-rules-section wb-table" style="width: 100%;">
                <tr><td class="BoardColumn"><strong>Forum Usage FAQ</strong></td></tr>
                <tr><td class="BoardRowB">
                    <p><strong>How do I post a new topic?</strong><br>
                    Open the board you want to post on and click <strong>Post New Topic</strong>. You must be logged in to post.</p>

                    <p><strong>How do I reply to a thread?</strong><br>
                    Open the thread and click <strong>Post Reply</strong>. If the thread is locked, normal users cannot reply.</p>

                    <p><strong>How do polls work?</strong><br>
                    On boards that allow posting, click <strong>Post Poll</strong>. Polls show live results, and logged-in users can vote once.</p>

                    <p><strong>Can I edit my posts?</strong><br>
                    Yes, within the board's edit time limit. Moderators may also edit posts when needed for moderation or cleanup. Edited posts may show edit metadata.</p>

                    <p><strong>What are the star icons next to usernames?</strong><br>
                    Stars are post-count ranks. They are just a visual forum rank and are not staff badges. Spamming to gain stars can get posts deleted or your account moderated.</p>

                    <p><strong>How do private messages work?</strong><br>
                    Logged-in users can send and receive private messages. Reported private messages may be reviewed by moderators. Staff cannot browse all private mail unless they have administrator-level access to the PM history tool.</p>

                    <p><strong>How do I report a post or private message?</strong><br>
                    Use the <strong>Report Message</strong> or <strong>Report This Message</strong> link. Include enough context for staff to understand the problem.</p>

                    <p><strong>Why did my post disappear?</strong><br>
                    It may have been moved, deleted, hidden, or merged by staff. If you are unsure, contact a moderator rather than reposting the same thing repeatedly.</p>

                    <p><strong>What does locked or sticky mean?</strong><br>
                    A locked thread cannot receive normal replies. A sticky thread is pinned near the top of the board because staff consider it useful or important.</p>

                    <p><strong>Are archive boards editable?</strong><br>
                    Archive areas may be read-only or restricted to preserve old forum history. Treat archived threads as historical records, not live discussion spaces.</p>

                    <p><strong>Who do I contact for account problems?</strong><br>
                    Contact a moderator or administrator. Include your username and a clear description of the issue.</p>
                </td></tr>
            </table>

